<div class="page-header"><h1>Frequently asked questions</h1>
<p>Sourced answers to the most common questions. If something is not covered here, <a href="/volunteer/">contact us</a>.</p></div>

<h2 class="mt-xl" class="faq-category" style="font-size:1.1rem;">Cost and taxes</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
<details class="faq"><summary>How much would the ACC property tax cost me?<span class="sr-only"> (expand)</span></summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>ACC's tax rate is $0.1034 per $100 of assessed valuation. For a $370,000 home, that is approximately $377 per year after the standard $5,000 homestead exemption. For a $500,000 home, approximately $512. ACC states this is the lowest community college tax rate in Texas. <a href="/calculator/">Use the calculator</a> for your specific estimate. Source: <a href="https://offices.austincc.edu/finance-and-administration/property-taxes/" target="_blank">ACC Finance</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>How much do Pflugerville residents save on tuition?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>In-district tuition and fees total $85/credit hour. Out-of-district: $286/credit hour. The savings is $201 per credit hour. A full-time student (30 credits/year) saves $6,030 per year. An associate degree (60 credits) saves $12,060. Source: <a href="https://admissions.austincc.edu/tuition-costs/" target="_blank">ACC Admissions</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>Has ACC raised tuition recently?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>No. ACC has not raised in-district tuition or general fees in 12 consecutive years, as of the 2025-26 academic year. The ACC Board of Trustees approves rates annually. Source: <a href="https://sites.austincc.edu/newsroom/2025/04/08/acc-maintains-tuition-for-12th-year-reinforces-commitment-to-college-affordability/" target="_blank">ACC Newsroom, April 2025</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>What about seniors and retirees?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>Homeowners 65+ or with disabilities receive a $75,000 additional homestead exemption (total $80,000). ACC also has a tax ceiling enacted in 2021: once you qualify, your ACC tax is frozen and cannot increase. For a newly annexed area, the ceiling begins the first year ACC taxes the property. Seniors also get free tuition for up to 6 credits per semester on a space-available basis. Source: <a href="https://offices.austincc.edu/finance-and-administration/property-taxes/" target="_blank">ACC Finance</a>, <a href="https://admissions.austincc.edu/tuition-costs/tuition-waivers-and-exemptions/" target="_blank">ACC Waivers</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>Do renters pay the ACC tax?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>Renters do not directly pay the property tax. However, they gain full access to in-district tuition rates. If you or anyone in your household considers ACC, the tuition savings apply immediately.</p></div></details>
</div>

<h2 class="mt-xl" class="faq-category" style="font-size:1.1rem;">Programs and access</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
<details class="faq"><summary>What programs does ACC offer?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>More than 100 programs in 10 areas of study: nursing (through BSN), welding, HVAC, plumbing, electrical, cybersecurity, advanced manufacturing, culinary arts, medical lab technology, logistics, business, and university transfer pathways. Full list: <a href="https://programs.austincc.edu/programs-by-area-of-study/" target="_blank">ACC Programs A-Z</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>What is the free tuition program and does it apply to PfISD?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>ACC's free tuition pilot (launched 2024) covers tuition and general fees for recent high school graduates and GED completers in the ACC service area. PfISD grads qualify. But out-of-district students still pay the $201/credit hour out-of-district fee. Joining the district eliminates that fee. Source: <a href="https://catalog.austincc.edu/college-entry/paying-for-college/acc-free-tuition-pilot-program/" target="_blank">ACC Free Tuition</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>What about dual credit for high school students?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>PfISD runs an ACC dual credit partnership. ACC eliminated the out-of-district fee for dual credit in Spring 2024. But when students graduate and continue at ACC, they re-enter as out-of-district. In-district status makes the transition seamless and affordable. Source: <a href="https://www.pfisd.net/programs/counseling/acc-dual-credit-partnership" target="_blank">PfISD Dual Credit</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>What is the difference between ACC's service area and in-district?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>Two different boundaries. The service area includes all ISDs where ACC provides services (including PfISD). The taxing district (in-district) includes only ISDs whose voters approved annexation. PfISD is in the service area but not the taxing district. That means PfISD students can attend ACC but pay the $201 out-of-district fee. Source: <a href="https://www.austincc.edu/about-acc/acc-district-service-area/" target="_blank">ACC District &amp; Service Area</a>.</p></div></details>
</div>

<h2 class="mt-xl" class="faq-category" style="font-size:1.1rem;">The vote and process</h2>
<div class="faq-list">
<details class="faq"><summary>Did Pflugerville already vote on this?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>Yes, in November 2018. The measure failed 53.45% to 46.55%. Since then: ACC launched free tuition (PfISD students still pay the out-of-district fee), Lockhart joined in 2024 and saw enrollment triple, and ACC extended its no-tuition-increase streak to 12 years. The conditions have changed. Source: <a href="https://communityimpact.com/austin/round-rock-pflugerville-hutto/vote/2018/11/06/early-voting-returns-show-pfisd-voters-rejecting-acc-annexation/" target="_blank">Community Impact, Nov 2018</a>.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>How does the petition work?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>Texas Education Code requires signatures from at least 5% of registered voters in PfISD territory. If the petition qualifies, the ACC Board calls an election. Only PfISD-area voters vote on the measure. If it passes, in-district benefits begin immediately upon certification.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>Does signing the petition mean I support ACC annexation?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>No. Signing puts the question on the November 2026 ballot so every registered voter in PfISD territory gets to decide. It does not commit you to voting yes. The last time voters had a say was 2018, and the conditions have changed. If you think voters deserve the choice, that's reason enough to sign.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>Is this a city decision or PfISD-wide?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>PfISD-wide. All registered voters within PfISD boundaries vote, including those outside Pflugerville city limits and in the ETJ. The city does not control the process.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>Does ACC advocate for this?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>No. ACC cannot advocate for or against annexation. The college can respond to questions and provide facts, but the decision rests with voters. This campaign is community-led and independent of ACC.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>What if nobody in my household attends ACC?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>ACC trains the nurses, electricians, HVAC techs, and IT workers your community relies on. Texas community colleges contribute nearly $10 billion annually to the state economy. Workers with associate degrees earn ~$8,788 more per year than HS diploma holders. The annual tax for a median home is about $377 ($1.03/day). The community benefits even for non-student households. And if anyone in your household ever wants retraining, the option is there at in-district rates.</p></div></details>

<details class="faq"><summary>Will ACC build a campus in Pflugerville?</summary>
<div class="faq-body"><p>ACC's service plan, published during the election process, will outline specific commitments. For reference: Lockhart voted yes in Nov 2024 and ACC opened a center within a year. Elgin voted yes in 2010 and got a full 65,000 sq ft campus by 2013. PfISD already has Career Academy infrastructure with ACC, and the new CTE center (2027) creates additional local capacity.</p></div></details>
</div>

